<article>

  <p>
    The three characteristics —
    <span class="pali" data-pali="anicca" data-en="impermanence">anicca</span>,
    <span class="pali" data-pali="dukkha" data-en="suffering; unsatisfactoriness">dukkha</span>,
    and <span class="pali" data-pali="anattā" data-en="non-self">anattā</span> — appear
    throughout the Pali canon as the Buddha's basic description of conditioned experience.
    They are not three separate insights to be collected sequentially. They are three
    angles on the same thing: what is actually true of the phenomena that constitute
    what we call a life.
  </p>

  <p>
    The canonical formulation appears in the Dhammapada and across the Aṅguttara
    <span class="pali" data-pali="nikāya" data-en="collection">Nikāya</span>:
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    "All formations are impermanent. All formations are suffering.
    All phenomena are non-self."
    <cite>— Dhp 277–279 (adapted)</cite>
  </blockquote>

  <p>
    The slight asymmetry in the third line — "phenomena" (dhammā) rather than
    "formations" (<span class="pali" data-pali="saṅkhārā" data-en="conditioned formations">saṅkhārā</span>)
    — is not incidental. Impermanence and suffering apply to conditioned things;
    non-self applies to everything, conditioned and unconditioned alike.
    There is no self to be found anywhere in experience.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Anicca — Impermanence</h2>

  <p>
    <span class="pali" data-pali="anicca" data-en="impermanence">Anicca</span> is the
    most immediately verifiable of the three. Every conditioned thing arises in dependence
    on conditions and passes away when those conditions change. Feelings arise and dissolve.
    Thoughts appear and are replaced. The body that woke up this morning is not quite
    the same body that will fall asleep tonight.
  </p>

  <p>
    The difficulty with anicca is not intellectual. Most people readily agree that things
    are impermanent. The difficulty is in how the mind actually operates — as though things
    will persist, as though this pleasant experience will last, as though the self having
    these experiences is stable and continuous. The agreement in principle does not
    automatically become a clear seeing of what is actually happening moment to moment.
  </p>

  <p>
    The practice implication of anicca is not resignation but attention. When impermanence
    is seen directly — in the rising and passing of breath, in the flicker of sensation,
    in the body's constant micro-adjustments — the mind loosens its grip on what was
    never stable to begin with. Not because it has decided to, but because the seeing
    itself changes what holding-on is trying to hold.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Dukkha — Pervasive Unsatisfactoriness</h2>

  <p>
    <span class="pali" data-pali="dukkha" data-en="suffering; unsatisfactoriness">Dukkha</span>
    is usually translated as "suffering," but the Pali covers a wider range than the
    English word suggests. The commentarial tradition distinguishes three types:
    <em>dukkha-dukkha</em> — the direct suffering of pain, illness, loss, and grief;
    <em>vipariṇāma-dukkha</em> — the suffering that comes from the inevitable change
    of pleasant things; and <em>saṅkhāra-dukkha</em> — the pervasive unsatisfactoriness
    that belongs to conditioned existence as such, regardless of whether any given moment
    is pleasant or painful.
  </p>

  <p>
    It is the third type that distinguishes the Buddhist diagnosis from ordinary
    unhappiness. Even when life is going well — when everything the mind wanted has
    arrived — there remains an undercurrent of instability, of contingency, of the
    awareness (however suppressed) that this too will change. The pleasant is pleasant,
    but it is not permanently pleasant. It is conditioned, which means it depends on
    factors outside of our control to sustain it.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is not a counsel of despair. The first noble truth does not say that
    everything is suffering or that happiness is impossible. It says that conditioned
    phenomena — however pleasant — cannot deliver the kind of unconditional stability
    the mind is implicitly seeking when it reaches for them. The direction the teaching
    points is not toward joylessness but toward a happiness that does not depend on
    conditions holding steady.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Anattā — The Absence of a Fixed Self</h2>

  <p>
    <span class="pali" data-pali="anattā" data-en="non-self">Anattā</span> is the
    most contested and philosophically demanding of the three. It is also the most
    distinctive — no other major Indian philosophical tradition at the time made a
    comparable claim about the absence of a permanent self.
  </p>

  <p>
    The argument is precise. In the Indian philosophical context, an
    <span class="pali" data-pali="attā" data-en="self">attā</span> (self) would
    need to be permanent, under one's control, and the ultimate subject of experience.
    The Buddha's challenge — applied systematically to each of the five
    <span class="pali" data-pali="khandha" data-en="aggregate">khandhas</span> in the
    Anattalakkhaṇa Sutta — is this: is form permanent or impermanent? If impermanent,
    is it satisfying or dukkha? If it is dukkha and subject to change, can it rightly
    be called "mine, what I am, my self"? In each case, the answer is no.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is not a claim that experience is not occurring, or that the conventional
    person does not exist. It is a claim about what kind of thing is actually found
    when one looks carefully. What is found is a process — conditioned, changing, without
    a stable center that owns or controls it. The <em>idea</em> of a self is something
    that arises within experience; it is not the knower standing behind experience.
  </p>

  <p>
    The common misreading takes anattā to mean "you do not exist" — a nihilistic claim
    the Buddha explicitly rejected. The teaching is more precise: the particular thing
    the word "self" points to — something permanent, in control, ultimately mine — is
    simply not what is found on close examination. That examination is not an argument
    to be settled but an investigation to be undertaken.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>How the Three Form One Teaching</h2>

  <p>
    The three characteristics are interrelated, not merely parallel. There is a logical
    sequence running through them: it is <em>because</em> things are impermanent that
    they are incapable of providing lasting satisfaction; and it is <em>because</em>
    they are impermanent and incapable of lasting satisfaction that they cannot constitute
    or belong to a permanent self.
  </p>

  <p>
    The sequence also works as an account of how suffering arises. The mind takes
    conditioned, impermanent phenomena and relates to them as though they were permanent,
    satisfying, and self. That mismatch between what things are and how the mind takes
    them to be is the root of
    <span class="pali" data-pali="dukkha" data-en="suffering">dukkha</span>. Seeing
    the three characteristics clearly is, in a direct sense, the correction of
    that mismatch.
  </p>

  <p>
    What makes the three characteristics a single teaching is not just logical
    entailment but practical convergence. A practitioner who sees
    <span class="pali" data-pali="anicca" data-en="impermanence">anicca</span> clearly
    will notice the dukkha of grasping what is impermanent. Noticing that, the question
    of whether there is a fixed self doing the grasping becomes more immediate. The three
    illuminate each other when brought to experience directly, not just considered
    as ideas.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>In Practice</h2>

  <p>
    The three characteristics are not propositions to be accepted on authority but
    qualities to be investigated in direct experience. The
    <span class="pali" data-pali="satipaṭṭhāna" data-en="foundations of mindfulness">satipaṭṭhāna</span>
    practice described in MN 10 is, in large part, a structured method for this
    investigation — applied to bodily sensations, to feelings, to mind states, and to
    phenomena — observing them as they arise, as they are present, as they pass away.
  </p>

  <p>
    The instruction is not to conclude that things are impermanent and then meditate
    with that conclusion as a background belief. It is to observe carefully enough that
    impermanence, unsatisfactoriness, and the absence of a fixed self are
    <em>seen</em> rather than inferred. The difference matters. A conclusion held as a
    view can be argued with, qualified, or forgotten. A characteristic that has been
    observed directly becomes the ground from which the rest of the path unfolds.
  </p>

</article>
